<h1 class="hero-h">Why AI Centers of Excellence <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">do not work.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Every consulting firm recommends an "AI Center of Excellence" — a centralized AI team to drive enterprise adoption. In practice, most CoEs become bottlenecks that slow adoption rather than accelerate it. Here is why and what to do instead.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The premise</span><h2 class="h2">The CoE model and its appeal</h2>
    <p class="body">AI CoE = centralized team that owns AI strategy, tool selection, governance, and often AI implementations across the business.</p>
    <p class="body">The appeal is obvious: consistency, governance, economies of scale, vendor relationships managed centrally.</p>
    <p class="body">The reality: most CoEs become approval bottlenecks. Functions wait for the CoE to bless deployments. Adoption slows. Innovation moves outside the CoE through unsanctioned tools.</p>
    </div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The 3 reasons CoEs fail</span><h2 class="h2">Structural issues</h2>
    <p class="body"><strong>1. They are too far from the work.</strong> Effective AI deployment requires deep understanding of the specific function's workflows. CoE generalists know AI; they do not know how marketing or CS actually operates.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>2. They become governance, not enablement.</strong> CoE staffing inevitably tilts toward policy, vendor management, and approvals — not building. Functions hit walls instead of getting help.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>3. They cannot scale to organizational pace.</strong> When every function wants AI now, a centralized team cannot match demand. Shadow AI deployments proliferate.</p>
    </div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">What works instead</span><h2 class="h2">Embedded model</h2>
    <p class="body"><strong>Pattern: light central governance + embedded function leads.</strong> Small central team (1-3 people) sets policy, approves vendors, runs training. Embedded function-level AI leads (one per function) drive workflow deployment.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>Function leads report to function heads.</strong> Not to the CoE. This keeps them close to the work and accountable for outcomes.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>The central team is enabler, not gatekeeper.</strong> Their KPIs are function-level AI usage and outcomes, not approvals processed.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>This pattern produces 3-5x faster deployment than centralized CoE models.</strong></p>
    </div></section>

